Write a one-page summary in your own words covering:
1.	What is AI? 
2.	What is Machine Learning? 
3.	What is Deep Learning? 
4.	What is Generative AI? 
5.	Difference between an LLM and a Diffusion M
Understanding AI, ML, Deep Learning, and Generative AI
1. What is AI?
Artificial Intelligence (AI) is the broad idea of building machines or software that can perform tasks which normally require human intelligence — things like recognizing images, understanding language, making decisions, or solving problems. AI isn't one single technology; it's an umbrella term that covers everything from simple rule-based systems (like a chatbot that follows a fixed script) to advanced systems that can learn and adapt on their own.
2. What is Machine Learning?
Machine Learning (ML) is a subset of AI. Instead of a programmer writing exact rules for every situation, ML systems learn patterns from data. For example, if you feed a system thousands of emails labeled "spam" or "not spam," it learns to spot spam on its own, without being explicitly told what makes an email spammy. The more (and better) data it sees, the more accurate it usually becomes.
3. What is Deep Learning?
Deep Learning is a further subset of Machine Learning that uses "neural networks" — structures loosely inspired by how neurons in the human brain connect and pass signals. These networks have many layers (hence "deep"), which allows them to automatically discover complex patterns in large amounts of data, like recognizing faces in photos or understanding speech. Deep learning is what powers most of today's cutting-edge AI, including image recognition and language models.
4. What is Generative AI?
Generative AI is a category of AI (usually built using deep learning) that doesn't just analyze or classify data — it creates new content. This could be text, images, music, code, or video. Tools like ChatGPT (text) or Midjourney (images) are examples. Instead of just answering "is this a cat or a dog," generative AI can produce a brand-new paragraph, picture, or piece of music based on what it has learned from existing examples.
5. Difference between an LLM and a Diffusion Model
•	A Large Language Model (LLM) is trained on massive amounts of text and specializes in understanding and generating language. It works by predicting the next word (or "token") in a sequence, one step at a time, which lets it write essays, answer questions, or hold conversations. Examples: GPT, Claude, Gemini.
•	A Diffusion Model is mainly used to generate images (and increasingly audio/video). It works very differently — it starts with random noise and gradually "cleans it up" step by step until a coherent image appears, guided by a text description. Examples: Stable Diffusion, DALL•E, Midjourney.
In short: LLMs are built for language and reasoning; diffusion models are built for generating visual (or audio) content from noise.
6. Three Ways AI Could Help a Coaching Institute
1.	Personalized learning paths – AI can analyze each student's strengths and weaknesses from test results and recommend customized practice material, helping slower learners catch up and advanced learners move ahead.
2.	Automated doubt-solving and support – A chatbot trained on the institute's syllabus can answer common student queries instantly, 24/7, reducing the workload on teachers for repetitive questions.
3.	Smarter administration and analytics – AI can help track attendance, predict which students are at risk of dropping out or underperforming, and generate performance reports automatically, saving staff hours of manual work.


